1. Select Your Operating System (OS):   Choose an operating system that best suits your preferences and project requirements. Download and Install Windows 11. https://www.microsoft.com/software-download/windows11y
Visit the Windows 11 Download Page: Go to the official Microsoft Windows 11 download page.

Select Installation Method: 
Windows 11 Installation Assistant: Best for upgrading a current Windows 10 device.
Create Windows 11 Installation Media: For clean installs using a USB or DVD.
Download Windows 11 Disk Image (ISO): For creating bootable media or virtual machines.
Follow Instructions: Each option has specific steps, including verifying system requirements, downloading tools, and running installers.
Requirements: A valid Windows 10 license, an internet connection,  adequate storage space (at least 9 GB for the installation assistant).




2. Install a Text Editor or Integrated Development Environment (IDE):   Select and install a text editor or IDE suitable for your programming languages and workflow. Download and Install Visual Studio Code. https://code.visualstudio.com/Download
Select and install a text editor or IDE suitable for your programming languages and workflow. Download and Install Visual Studio Code. https://code.visualstudio.com/Download
To get started with Visual Studio Code (VSCode) on Windows, first download and install it from the VSCode website. Follow the prompts in the installer to complete the setup. Next, set up version control by installing Git. Download the Windows installer from the Git website, run it, and make sure to add Git to your system PATH during installation. After installing Git, open a terminal (Command Prompt or Git Bash) and configure your Git username and email using git config --global user.name "Your Name" and git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com". Then, create a GitHub account at the GitHub website if you don't already have one and set up a new repository.




3. Set Up Version Control System:   Install Git and configure it on your local machine. Create a GitHub account for hosting your repositories. Initialize a Git repository for your project and make your first commit. https://github.com
Install Git and configure it on your local machine. Create a GitHub account for hosting your repositories. Initialize a Git repository for your project and make your first commit. https://github.com
To set up Git version control, download Git from their website, install it, and make sure to add it to your system PATH. In a terminal, configure your Git username and email using the appropriate commands. If you don't have a GitHub account, create one to store your code repositories.
